        args='{"final_result": "## Starlink vs. OneWeb Revenue Multiple Analysis\\n\\n### Data Inputs\\n\\n**SpaceX (Starlink) – Connectivity Segment (from S-1 filed May 20, 2026):**\\n- Q1 2026 Connectivity Revenue (3 months ended March 31, 2026): **$3,257 million**\\n- Q1 2025 Connectivity Revenue: $2,475 million (Q1 YoY growth: +31.6%)\\n- Full Year 2025 Connectivity Revenue: **$11,387 million** (YoY growth: +49.8%)\\n- Full Year 2024 Connectivity Revenue: $7,599 million\\n\\n**Eutelsat OneWeb – LEO Segment (from Eutelsat H1 FY2025-26 earnings):**\\n- H1 FY2025-26 LEO Revenue (6 months ended December 31, 2025): **€110.5 million**\\n- YoY growth: ~59.7% (like-for-like)\\n- LEO represents ~20% of total Eutelsat group revenue and ~36% of Connectivity revenue\\n\\n**EUR/USD Exchange Rate:** 1.1746 (December 31, 2025 spot close)\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Annualization to a Common Basis\\n\\n| Metric | SpaceX Connectivity | OneWeb LEO |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| Reported Period | Q1 2026 (3 months) | H1 FY2025-26 (6 months) |\\n| Reported Revenue | $3,257M | €110.5M |\\n| Annualization Method | ×4 | ×2 |\\n| **Annualized Revenue (local currency)** | **$13,028M** | **€221.0M** |\\n| **Annualized Revenue (USD)** | **$13,028M** | **$259.6M** |\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Implied Revenue Multiple\\n\\n$$\\\\text{Multiple} = \\\\frac{\\\\$13{,}028M}{\\\\$259.6M} = \\\\boxed{50.2\\\\times}$$\\n\\n**Sensitivity check using SpaceX\'s actual FY2025 Connectivity revenue ($11,387M) vs. OneWeb\'s annualized figure:**\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{\\\\$11{,}387M}{\\\\$259.6M} = 43.9\\\\times$$\\n\\n**The Starlink run-rate exceeds OneWeb\'s by approximately 44–50× on a revenue basis.**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### What This Reveals About Relative Commercial Maturity\\n\\n**1. Scale Disparity:** Starlink\'s annualized Connectivity revenue of ~$13 billion dwarfs OneWeb\'s ~$260 million by roughly 50 times. Starlink has achieved a commercial scale comparable to a mid-cap telecom operator; OneWeb remains at the scale of a niche satellite services provider.\\n\\n**2. Model Differences Driving Scale Gap:**\\n- **Starlink\'s direct-to-consumer (DTC) model** accounts for $2,148M of Q1 2026 Connectivity revenue (~66%), enabling massive subscriber acquisition (104.7% subscriber growth in the quarter). This consumer flywheel generates enormous volume.\\n- **OneWeb operates primarily as a B2B/wholesale** capacity provider, selling through distribution partners (e.g., Hughes/EchoStar, BT, government agencies). This limits direct subscriber scale but may offer more predictable enterprise contracts.\\n\\n**3. Growth Trajectories:**\\n- OneWeb\'s ~60% like-for-like H1 growth outpaces SpaceX\'s ~50% FY2025 Connectivity growth and ~32% Q1 2026/Q1 2025 quarterly growth. However, growing 60% from a €70M H1 base adds ~€42M; SpaceX\'s 50% growth from a $7.6B base added ~$3.8B. In absolute terms, SpaceX is adding roughly 70–90× more revenue per year than OneWeb.\\n\\n**4. Profitability Contrast:**\\n- SpaceX\'s Connectivity segment generated **$1,188M in segment operating income** in Q1 2026 alone (~36.5% margin), suggesting the segment is solidly profitable.\\n- Eutelsat\'s group-level adjusted EBITDA margin *declined* from 55.2% to 52.1%, partly due to LEO ramp-up costs. OneWeb\'s standalone LEO profitability is not separately disclosed, but the segment was previously loss-making as the constellation was being deployed.\\n\\n**5. Consumer Scale as Moat:** Starlink\'s reported 104.7% subscriber growth with declining ARPU (−22.9%) signals aggressive penetration pricing in international markets — a classic scale-play strategy. OneWeb has no comparable consumer subscriber base to leverage.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Disclosure Differences Limiting Precision of the Comparison\\n\\n| Limitation | Impact |\\n|---|---|\\n| **Currency mismatch** | OneWeb reports in EUR (IFRS); SpaceX in USD (US GAAP). FX conversion introduces noise; the EUR/USD rate ranged from ~1.04–1.18 during 2025, which could swing the USD-equivalent OneWeb figure by ±$30M. |\\n| **Fiscal year misalignment** | Eutelsat\'s fiscal year runs July–June; SpaceX reports on a calendar-year basis. OneWeb\'s H1 (Jul–Dec 2025) does not align with SpaceX\'s Q1 (Jan–Mar 2026), making the annualized figures represent partially overlapping but non-identical forward periods. |\\n| **Segment definition asymmetry** | SpaceX \\"Connectivity\\" includes **Starlink kit hardware sales** ($380M in Q1 2026, ~12% of segment revenue) alongside service revenue. OneWeb\'s LEO revenue appears to be predominantly services/capacity, with hardware (user terminals) sold separately or through partners and potentially not captured in Eutelsat\'s LEO line. |\\n| **Accounting standards** | SpaceX uses US GAAP; Eutelsat uses IFRS. Revenue recognition timing, capitalization policies, and intercompany eliminations may differ. |\\n| **Consolidation scope (SpaceX)** | The SpaceX S-1 financials are retrospectively recast under common-control accounting to include **xAI** (merged Feb 2, 2026) and **X Holdings** (merged into xAI Mar 28, 2025). The Connectivity segment figures should be Starlink-specific, but the broader consolidation affects total-company context. |\\n| **Annualization assumes flat seasonality** | Multiplying Q1 × 4 and H1 × 2 assumes no seasonal variation. Starlink may exhibit seasonality (e.g., Q4 holiday-driven kit sales), and OneWeb may see uneven enterprise contract timing. |\\n| **Customer mix opacity** | SpaceX discloses Consumer ($2,148M) vs. Enterprise & Government ($1,109M) for Connectivity. OneWeb does not separately break out LEO revenue by customer vertical in comparable detail, limiting a like-for-like segment-level matching. |\\n| **ARPU / subscriber count disclosure** | SpaceX discloses subscriber counts and ARPU trends, enabling unit-economic analysis. Eutelsat discloses LEO revenue at the segment level but does not provide comparable per-subscriber economics for OneWeb\'s LEO connectivity users. |\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Conclusion\\n\\nStarlink\'s run-rate revenue exceeds OneWeb\'s by approximately **50×**, reflecting a fundamental gap in commercial maturity: Starlink has successfully executed a direct-to-consumer mass-market strategy that generates $13B+ in annualized revenue with positive operating margins, while OneWeb remains a B2B-focused wholesale operator at ~$260M annualized. Although OneWeb is growing faster in percentage terms (~60% vs. ~32–50%), the absolute dollar increments are orders of magnitude smaller. The comparison is materially imprecise due to currency, fiscal-year, segment-definition, and accounting-standard differences between Eutelsat\'s IFRS H1 earnings and SpaceX\'s US GAAP SEC filing.\\n\\n---\\n\\n**Sources:**\\n- SpaceX S-1 filing (May 20, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\n- Eutelsat H1 FY2025-26 results (via Investing.com and broadbandtvnews.com, February 2026)\\n- EUR/USD FX data: price_history (December 31, 2025 close: 1.1746)"}',
        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## Starlink vs. OneWeb Revenue Multiple Analysis\n\n### Data Inputs\n\n**SpaceX (Starlink) – Connectivity Segment (from S-1 filed May 20, 2026):**\n- Q1 2026 Connectivity Revenue (3 months ended March 31, 2026): **$3,257 million**\n- Q1 2025 Connectivity Revenue: $2,475 million (Q1 YoY growth: +31.6%)\n- Full Year 2025 Connectivity Revenue: **$11,387 million** (YoY growth: +49.8%)\n- Full Year 2024 Connectivity Revenue: $7,599 million\n\n**Eutelsat OneWeb – LEO Segment (from Eutelsat H1 FY2025-26 earnings):**\n- H1 FY2025-26 LEO Revenue (6 months ended December 31, 2025): **€110.5 million**\n- YoY growth: ~59.7% (like-for-like)\n- LEO represents ~20% of total Eutelsat group revenue and ~36% of Connectivity revenue\n\n**EUR/USD Exchange Rate:** 1.1746 (December 31, 2025 spot close)\n\n---\n\n### Annualization to a Common Basis\n\n| Metric | SpaceX Connectivity | OneWeb LEO |\n|---|---|---|\n| Reported Period | Q1 2026 (3 months) | H1 FY2025-26 (6 months) |\n| Reported Revenue | $3,257M | €110.5M |\n| Annualization Method | ×4 | ×2 |\n| **Annualized Revenue (local currency)** | **$13,028M** | **€221.0M** |\n| **Annualized Revenue (USD)** | **$13,028M** | **$259.6M** |\n\n---\n\n### Implied Revenue Multiple\n\n$$\\text{Multiple} = \\frac{\\$13{,}028M}{\\$259.6M} = \\boxed{50.2\\times}$$\n\n**Sensitivity check using SpaceX\'s actual FY2025 Connectivity revenue ($11,387M) vs. OneWeb\'s annualized figure:**\n\n$$\\frac{\\$11{,}387M}{\\$259.6M} = 43.9\\times$$\n\n**The Starlink run-rate exceeds OneWeb\'s by approximately 44–50× on a revenue basis.**\n\n---\n\n### What This Reveals About Relative Commercial Maturity\n\n**1. Scale Disparity:** Starlink\'s annualized Connectivity revenue of ~$13 billion dwarfs OneWeb\'s ~$260 million by roughly 50 times. Starlink has achieved a commercial scale comparable to a mid-cap telecom operator; OneWeb remains at the scale of a niche satellite services provider.\n\n**2. Model Differences Driving Scale Gap:**\n- **Starlink\'s direct-to-consumer (DTC) model** accounts for $2,148M of Q1 2026 Connectivity revenue (~66%), enabling massive subscriber acquisition (104.7% subscriber growth in the quarter). This consumer flywheel generates enormous volume.\n- **OneWeb operates primarily as a B2B/wholesale** capacity provider, selling through distribution partners (e.g., Hughes/EchoStar, BT, government agencies). This limits direct subscriber scale but may offer more predictable enterprise contracts.\n\n**3. Growth Trajectories:**\n- OneWeb\'s ~60% like-for-like H1 growth outpaces SpaceX\'s ~50% FY2025 Connectivity growth and ~32% Q1 2026/Q1 2025 quarterly growth. However, growing 60% from a €70M H1 base adds ~€42M; SpaceX\'s 50% growth from a $7.6B base added ~$3.8B. In absolute terms, SpaceX is adding roughly 70–90× more revenue per year than OneWeb.\n\n**4. Profitability Contrast:**\n- SpaceX\'s Connectivity segment generated **$1,188M in segment operating income** in Q1 2026 alone (~36.5% margin), suggesting the segment is solidly profitable.\n- Eutelsat\'s group-level adjusted EBITDA margin *declined* from 55.2% to 52.1%, partly due to LEO ramp-up costs. OneWeb\'s standalone LEO profitability is not separately disclosed, but the segment was previously loss-making as the constellation was being deployed.\n\n**5. Consumer Scale as Moat:** Starlink\'s reported 104.7% subscriber growth with declining ARPU (−22.9%) signals aggressive penetration pricing in international markets — a classic scale-play strategy. OneWeb has no comparable consumer subscriber base to leverage.\n\n---\n\n### Disclosure Differences Limiting Precision of the Comparison\n\n| Limitation | Impact |\n|---|---|\n| **Currency mismatch** | OneWeb reports in EUR (IFRS); SpaceX in USD (US GAAP). FX conversion introduces noise; the EUR/USD rate ranged from ~1.04–1.18 during 2025, which could swing the USD-equivalent OneWeb figure by ±$30M. |\n| **Fiscal year misalignment** | Eutelsat\'s fiscal year runs July–June; SpaceX reports on a calendar-year basis. OneWeb\'s H1 (Jul–Dec 2025) does not align with SpaceX\'s Q1 (Jan–Mar 2026), making the annualized figures represent partially overlapping but non-identical forward periods. |\n| **Segment definition asymmetry** | SpaceX "Connectivity" includes **Starlink kit hardware sales** ($380M in Q1 2026, ~12% of segment revenue) alongside service revenue. OneWeb\'s LEO revenue appears to be predominantly services/capacity, with hardware (user terminals) sold separately or through partners and potentially not captured in Eutelsat\'s LEO line. |\n| **Accounting standards** | SpaceX uses US GAAP; Eutelsat uses IFRS. Revenue recognition timing, capitalization policies, and intercompany eliminations may differ. |\n| **Consolidation scope (SpaceX)** | The SpaceX S-1 financials are retrospectively recast under common-control accounting to include **xAI** (merged Feb 2, 2026) and **X Holdings** (merged into xAI Mar 28, 2025). The Connectivity segment figures should be Starlink-specific, but the broader consolidation affects total-company context. |\n| **Annualization assumes flat seasonality** | Multiplying Q1 × 4 and H1 × 2 assumes no seasonal variation. Starlink may exhibit seasonality (e.g., Q4 holiday-driven kit sales), and OneWeb may see uneven enterprise contract timing. |\n| **Customer mix opacity** | SpaceX discloses Consumer ($2,148M) vs. Enterprise & Government ($1,109M) for Connectivity. OneWeb does not separately break out LEO revenue by customer vertical in comparable detail, limiting a like-for-like segment-level matching. |\n| **ARPU / subscriber count disclosure** | SpaceX discloses subscriber counts and ARPU trends, enabling unit-economic analysis. Eutelsat discloses LEO revenue at the segment level but does not provide comparable per-subscriber economics for OneWeb\'s LEO connectivity users. |\n\n---\n\n### Conclusion\n\nStarlink\'s run-rate revenue exceeds OneWeb\'s by approximately **50×**, reflecting a fundamental gap in commercial maturity: Starlink has successfully executed a direct-to-consumer mass-market strategy that generates $13B+ in annualized revenue with positive operating margins, while OneWeb remains a B2B-focused wholesale operator at ~$260M annualized. Although OneWeb is growing faster in percentage terms (~60% vs. ~32–50%), the absolute dollar increments are orders of magnitude smaller. The comparison is materially imprecise due to currency, fiscal-year, segment-definition, and accounting-standard differences between Eutelsat\'s IFRS H1 earnings and SpaceX\'s US GAAP SEC filing.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- SpaceX S-1 filing (May 20, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\n- Eutelsat H1 FY2025-26 results (via Investing.com and broadbandtvnews.com, February 2026)\n- EUR/USD FX data: price_history (December 31, 2025 close: 1.1746)'
